In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April 2013 as National Sexual Assault Awareness and Prevention Month. He acknowledges the progress that has been made in addressing sexual assault over the past 20 years, but emphasizes that there is still work to be done. He highlights the disproportionate impact of sexual assault on children, teens, and young women, as well as certain groups like Native American women. President Obama also mentions the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act, which he recently signed, and discusses the importance of supporting survivors and holding offenders accountable. He calls for efforts to change the culture surrounding sexual violence and encourages Americans to get involved in prevention efforts. The article concludes with President Obama urging all Americans to support survivors of sexual assault and work together to prevent these crimes in their communities.